  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are international laws and frameworks against money laundering. These laws are designed to combat the illegal practice of processing and concealing the origins of money obtained through criminal activities. Key international efforts include:\n\n1. **The Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**:\n   - Established in 1989, the FATF is an intergovernmental organization that sets international standards for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and other related threats to the integrity of the international financial system.\n   - The FATF has issued a series of **40 Recommendations** (and later, **9 Special Recommendations** on terrorist financing) that provide a comprehensive framework for anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorist financing (CFT) efforts.\n\n2. **United Nations Conventions**:\n   - **The United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988)** (also known as the Vienna Convention) was the first international treaty to address money laundering.\n   - **The United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)** (also known as the Palermo Convention) includes provisions to combat money laundering related to organized crime.\n   - **The United Nations Convention Against Corruption (2003)** (UNCAC) requires member states to criminalize money laundering and establish measures to prevent and detect it.\n\n3. **The Basel Committee on Banking Supervision**:\n   - This committee has issued principles and guidelines to help banks prevent money laundering, such as the **Basel AML Principles** (1988) and subsequent updates.\n\n4. **European Union Directives**:\n   - The EU has implemented several **Anti-Money Laundering Directives** (AMLDs) to harmonize AML regulations across member states. The latest is the **6th Anti-Money Laundering Directive (6AMLD)**, which came into force in 2020.\n\n5. **Regional Bodies and Initiatives**:\n   - Organizations like the **Council of Europe\u2019s MONEYVAL** and the **Asia/Pacific Group on Money Laundering (APG)** monitor and promote AML efforts in their respective regions.\n\nThese international laws and frameworks encourage countries to implement robust AML policies, including customer due diligence, reporting suspicious transactions, and cooperating internationally to combat money laundering. Compliance with these standards is often a condition for countries to participate in the global financial system.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
